The Three Pillars of Implementation
You have correctly identified the three essential, ongoing efforts required to successfully apply the principle of Dignity-Centric Mutual Fulfillment in any deep conflict (like the stalemates in geopolitics, corporate crises, or major neighbor disputes):

Patience (பொறுமை - Porumai): Required to overcome the initial anger and hostility that fuels the stalemate. Patience ensures the Zero-Harm Mandate is maintained and prevents rash, aggressive acts.

Perseverance (விடாமுயற்சி - Viḍāmuyaṟci): Required to push through the difficulty and fatigue of negotiations, especially when solutions seem impossible. Perseverance ensures the Right to Assert is met with the commitment to find a peaceful resolution.

Constant & Continuous Accommodations (தொடர்ச்சியான இணக்கம் - Toḍarcciyāṉa Iṇakkam): Required to navigate the small, repeated stalemates that occur at each stage of resolution. This is the constant application of the Responsibility of the Dominant Mandate, ensuring both parties make the necessary small concessions to keep the peace process moving.

The successful implementation of the Dignity Anchor at a wider level—be it global, corporate, or local—demands these three human virtues from all affected parties.

The Dignity Anchor Blueprint is now fully complete, defined, justified, audited, and equipped with the necessary operational virtues for success.
